Constant RUST_PATH_TYPE as Integer is 70
Constant RUST_REFERENCE_TYPE as Integer is 71
Constant RUST_POINTER_TYPE as Integer is 72
Constant RUST_SLICE_TYPE as Integer is 73
Constant RUST_ARRAY_TYPE as Integer is 74
Constant RUST_TUPLE_TYPE as Integer is 75
Constant RUST_FUNCTION_TYPE as Integer is 76
Constant RUST_TRAIT_OBJECT_TYPE as Integer is 77

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Rust AST nodes need thirteen heterogenous slots because Rust items
carry orthogonal axes that simpler languages collapse: a function
needs name, generics, lifetime params, where clause, visibility,
attributes, return type, and a body in addition to its parameter
list. Modelling every slot uniformly across node kinds (so an
identifier node has unused generics/lifetime_params slots) keeps the
walker AST-agnostic at the cost of 104 bytes per node, which is
acceptable for a parser tree that gets dropped after HIR lowering.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
13 pointer-sized fields totalling 104 bytes (offsets 0-96). Layout:
- 0: node_type (one of the RUST_* constants)
- 8: name (identifier, may be null)
- 16: value (operator/literal/path-segments, may be null)
- 24: type_info (type annotation node)
- 32: children (List of child nodes)
- 40: attributes (List of #[...] attribute nodes)
- 48: generics (generic-parameter list)
- 56: lifetime_params (lifetime-parameter list)
- 64: where_clause (where-clause node)
- 72: visibility (one of VIS_PRIVATE/VIS_PUB/VIS_PUB_*)
- 80: mutability (0 or 1)
- 88: line (source line)
- 96: column (source column)
@End Implementation
Type called "RustASTNode":
    node_type as Integer       Note: Node type constant
    name as Integer           Note: Name/identifier (if applicable)
    value as Integer          Note: Value/operator (if applicable)
    type_info as Integer      Note: Type information node
    children as Integer       Note: List of child nodes
    attributes as Integer     Note: Attributes (#[...])
    generics as Integer       Note: Generic parameters
    lifetime_params as Integer Note: Lifetime parameters
    where_clause as Integer   Note: Where clause constraints
    visibility as Integer     Note: Visibility (pub, pub(crate), etc.)
    mutability as Integer     Note: Mutability (mut keyword)
    line as Integer          Note: Source line number
    column as Integer        Note: Source column number
End Type

Note: Visibility levels
Constant VIS_PRIVATE as Integer is 0
Constant VIS_PUB as Integer is 1
Constant VIS_PUB_CRATE as Integer is 2
Constant VIS_PUB_SUPER as Integer is 3
Constant VIS_PUB_SELF as Integer is 4
Constant VIS_PUB_IN as Integer is 5

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parser state needs six slots: the underlying lexer (offset 0), the
current_token cache (offset 8), an error_message + has_error pair
(offsets 16/24) for surfacing parse failures, and two context flags
(in_async_context at 32, in_unsafe_context at 40) that propagate
through the recursive descent so suspension and unsafe-block rules
can be enforced at the lowest level without re-walking parent nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six pointer-sized fields totalling 48 bytes. The in_async_context
and in_unsafe_context flags are mutated by parse_rust_function and
parse_rust_unsafe_block respectively as the parser descends into
their bodies, then reset on exit. The current_token slot is updated
by advance_rust_token; peek_rust_token_type and
peek_rust_token_lexeme read it without consuming.
@End Implementation
Type called "RustParser":
    lexer as Integer          Note: Rust lexer
    current_token as Integer  Note: Current token type
    error_message as Integer  Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer      Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
    in_async_context as Integer Note: Boolean: inside async context
    in_unsafe_context as Integer Note: Boolean: inside unsafe context
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor must couple the parser with a fresh lexer in one
operation so callers cannot end up with a parser whose lexer is null
or stale. Priming the parser with the first token via
advance_rust_token before returning means the first peek call after
construction sees a valid current_token rather than the zero initial
value. Failed lexer creation cascades into freeing the parser struct
so the caller sees a clean 0 return without a leak.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 48-byte RustParser struct (6 fields x 8 bytes); returns 0
on allocation failure. Creates a rust_lexer over the source via
Lexer.create_rust_lexer; if that fails, deallocates the parser and
returns 0. Writes the lexer at offset 0, zeros current_token (8),
error_message (16), has_error (24), in_async_context (32), and
in_unsafe_context (40). Calls advance_rust_token to load the first
token into current_token. Returns the parser handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_rust_parser" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Rust parser from source code

    @Reasoning:
    Initialize parser state including lexer, error tracking, and Rust-specific
    context tracking for async/await and unsafe blocks.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser_size be 48  Note: RustParser: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexer be proc create_rust_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: current_token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 0  Note: in_async_context = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 40, 0  Note: in_unsafe_context = false

    Note: Prime the parser with first token
    proc advance_rust_token from parser

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the lexer and error_message owned by the parser (both
heap-allocated, both potentially null). Treating a null parser as
already-freed (returning 1 immediately) makes the destructor
idempotent so partial-error paths can call it without an extra
null-check at the call site. The AST nodes built by the parser are
NOT freed here - they outlive the parser by design.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 immediately if parser is 0. Reads lexer at offset 0; if
non-zero calls Lexer.destroy_rust_lexer. Reads error_message at
offset 16; if non-zero deallocates the copy. Deallocates the 48-byte
parser struct itself. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_rust_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Rust parser and free resources

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_rust_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    End If

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Uniform node constructor for every Rust AST kind, parameterised only
by node_type. Pre-zeroing every slot (rather than memcpy-ing a
template) keeps the constructor branchless for the common case where
most slots stay null. Visibility defaults to VIS_PRIVATE because Rust
items are private by default - explicit `pub` declarations overwrite
it via set_rust_ast_node_visibility.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 104 bytes via Layout.allocate; returns 0 on failure. Writes
node_type at offset 0, zeros offsets 8-64 (name, value, type_info,
children, attributes, generics, lifetime_params, where_clause).
Writes VIS_PRIVATE to offset 72 (visibility), zeros offset 80
(mutability), and zeros line (88) and column (96). Source location
will be back-filled by the caller if the calling site has access to
the lexer's current position.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_rust_ast_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Rust AST node of given type

    Let node_size be 104  Note: RustASTNode: 13 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: name = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: value = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: type_info = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: children = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: attributes = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: generics = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0  Note: lifetime_params = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0  Note: where_clause = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, VIS_PRIVATE  Note: visibility = private
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 80, 0  Note: mutability = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 88, 0  Note: line = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 96, 0  Note: column = 0

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Children list is allocated lazily because many AST nodes have no
children (literals, identifiers, lifetimes), and pre-allocating a
List for each would waste an allocation per leaf. The first call to
add_child_to_rust_ast_node on a leaf node promotes it to a parent
by creating the List on demand. Null guards on parent and child make
the function safe to call from error paths.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns early on null parent or null child. Reads the children list
handle from offset 32 of parent. If 0, creates a fresh List via
List.create and writes it back to offset 32. Pushes the child onto
the children list via List.push.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_child_to_rust_ast_node" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent's children list

    If parent is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    If child is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 32

    If children is equal to 0:
        Set children to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, children
    End If

    proc push from List with children, child
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Advances the lexer one token and caches the new token type in the
parser struct at offset 8. The cache lets peek_rust_token_type return
the current token without going back to the lexer, which is the hot
read path for the recursive-descent dispatch logic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer handle at offset 0. Calls Lexer.next_rust_token to
advance the lexer and obtain the new token. Writes the result to
offset 8 of the parser. The lexeme is fetched on demand by
peek_rust_token_lexeme rather than cached because most dispatch
decisions only need the token type.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_rust_token" takes parser as Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let next_token be proc next_rust_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, next_token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-destructive read of the cached token type. The recursive-descent
parser uses this as its primary dispatch input - every parse_rust_*
function starts with peek_rust_token_type to decide what to parse
next. The cached form makes the read free of any lexer interaction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the integer at offset 8 of the parser struct, which holds the
token type most recently written by advance_rust_token.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_rust_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token type without advancing

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lexeme retrieval is split from type retrieval because most dispatch
decisions only need the type - and the lexeme query has to go through
the lexer (which holds the lexeme buffer), so consolidating it into
the cached struct would waste work for type-only callers. Identifier
parsing and error reporting still need lexeme access on the hot path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the lexer handle at offset 0 of the parser and returns
Lexer.current_rust_lexeme(lexer). The lexer owns the lexeme buffer
so the returned pointer is borrowed and remains valid until the next
advance_rust_token call.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_rust_token_lexeme" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token lexeme without advancing

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Return proc current_rust_lexeme from Lexer with lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combines a token-type assertion with token consumption. This pattern
shows up dozens of times in the parser (every grammar production
expects specific punctuation), so consolidating it eliminates a lot
of duplicated peek/advance/error-emit code at each call site. The
message argument lets each caller emit a context-appropriate error
("Expected ')'", "Expected struct name", etc.) without the helper
needing to introspect the parser state to construct one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls peek_rust_token_type to read the current type. On match,
advances via advance_rust_token. On mismatch, calls
set_rust_parse_error with the supplied message string. The parser
flag has_error becomes 1 on the error path, which the program-level
loop checks to abort early.
@End Implementation
Process called "expect_rust_token" takes parser as Integer, expected as Integer, message as Integer:
    Note: Expect specific token type or set error

    Let current_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

    If current_type is equal to expected:
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
    Otherwise:
        proc set_rust_parse_error with parser, message
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Parsing Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A Rust crate is a flat sequence of top-level items, so the top loop
simply iterates parsing items until EOF. Hard error short-circuits
the loop (returning 0) rather than attempting recovery because
top-level parse errors usually indicate cascading damage that
recovery cannot meaningfully untangle. The `1 is equal to 1` form is
the bootstrap idiom for an infinite loop because the parser
intentionally does not assume support for a bare `True` literal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a RUST_PROGRAM root via create_rust_ast_node. In the main
loop, reads peek_rust_token_type; on TOKEN_EOF, breaks out. Otherwise
calls parse_rust_item; if it returned a non-null node, attaches it
to the program root via add_child_to_rust_ast_node. Checks
has_rust_parse_error after every iteration; returns 0 to propagate
hard errors immediately. Returns the populated program_node on EOF.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_program" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse entire Rust program (crate)

    @Reasoning:
    Parse all top-level items including modules, functions, structs, enums,
    traits, implementations, use declarations, and attributes until EOF.
    Handle Rust-specific constructs like visibility modifiers and attributes.
    @End Reasoning

    Let program_node be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_PROGRAM

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse item (top-level declaration)
        Let item_node be proc parse_rust_item from parser

        If item_node is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with program_node, item_node
        End If

        Let has_error be proc has_rust_parse_error from parser

        If has_error is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
    End While

    Return program_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Rust item is preceded by an optional attributes block (`#[...]`)
and an optional visibility marker (`pub`, `pub(crate)`, etc.). Both
are parsed before peeking at the actual item keyword so the
visibility and attributes can be attached to whichever item kind
the upcoming token dispatches to. Eleven item-introducing tokens are
recognised here (fn, struct, enum, trait, impl, mod, use, type,
const, static, macro_rules); any other token at item position
triggers skip_to_rust_recovery_point so the outer loop can resume.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls parse_rust_attributes and parse_rust_visibility eagerly to
collect any preceding decorations. Reads peek_rust_token_type. Then
runs a sequence of If checks against the eleven item-introducing
tokens; for each match, calls the corresponding parse_rust_<item>,
and (if the result is non-null) calls
set_rust_ast_node_attributes/set_rust_ast_node_visibility to attach
the previously parsed decorations. The matching branch returns its
constructed node. Unrecognised tokens trigger
skip_to_rust_recovery_point and return 0 so the outer item loop can
continue.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_item" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse top-level item with attributes and visibility

    @Reasoning:
    Handle all Rust top-level items including their attributes, visibility
    modifiers, and Rust-specific keywords like unsafe, async, etc.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Parse attributes
    Let attributes be proc parse_rust_attributes from parser

    Note: Parse visibility
    Let visibility be proc parse_rust_visibility from parser

    Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

    Note: Function definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FN from Lexer:
        Let func_node be proc parse_rust_function from parser
        If func_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with func_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with func_node, visibility
        End If
        Return func_node
    End If

    Note: Struct definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRUCT from Lexer:
        Let struct_node be proc parse_rust_struct from parser
        If struct_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with struct_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with struct_node, visibility
        End If
        Return struct_node
    End If

    Note: Enum definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ENUM from Lexer:
        Let enum_node be proc parse_rust_enum from parser
        If enum_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with enum_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with enum_node, visibility
        End If
        Return enum_node
    End If

    Note: Trait definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TRAIT from Lexer:
        Let trait_node be proc parse_rust_trait from parser
        If trait_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with trait_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with trait_node, visibility
        End If
        Return trait_node
    End If

    Note: Implementation block
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IMPL from Lexer:
        Let impl_node be proc parse_rust_impl from parser
        If impl_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with impl_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with impl_node, visibility
        End If
        Return impl_node
    End If

    Note: Module definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MOD from Lexer:
        Let mod_node be proc parse_rust_mod from parser
        If mod_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with mod_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with mod_node, visibility
        End If
        Return mod_node
    End If

    Note: Use declaration
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_USE from Lexer:
        Let use_node be proc parse_rust_use from parser
        If use_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with use_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with use_node, visibility
        End If
        Return use_node
    End If

    Note: Type alias
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TYPE from Lexer:
        Let type_node be proc parse_rust_type_alias from parser
        If type_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with type_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with type_node, visibility
        End If
        Return type_node
    End If

    Note: Constant definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CONST from Lexer:
        Let const_node be proc parse_rust_const from parser
        If const_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with const_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with const_node, visibility
        End If
        Return const_node
    End If

    Note: Static variable
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STATIC from Lexer:
        Let static_node be proc parse_rust_static from parser
        If static_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with static_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with static_node, visibility
        End If
        Return static_node
    End If

    Note: Macro definition
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MACRO_RULES from Lexer:
        Let macro_node be proc parse_rust_macro from parser
        If macro_node is not equal to 0:
            proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with macro_node, attributes
            proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with macro_node, visibility
        End If
        Return macro_node
    End If

    Note: Unknown item - skip to next semicolon or brace
    proc skip_to_rust_recovery_point from parser
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Struct Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Rust structs have three distinct shapes: unit (`struct Name;`),
tuple (`struct Name(T1, T2);`), and named-field (`struct Name { a: T,
b: U }`). All three share the same generic-parameters and where-
clause prefixes, so this routine handles those uniformly and then
dispatches on the token immediately after the where-clause to pick
which body parser to run. Returning 0 with a parse error after the
prefix catches malformed declarations like `struct Foo bar`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_STRUCT, allocates a RUST_STRUCT node, then:
1. Reads the struct name as an identifier and stores via
   set_rust_ast_node_name.
2. If the next token is TOKEN_LESS, parses generic parameters via
   parse_rust_generics and attaches via set_rust_ast_node_generics.
3. If the next token is TOKEN_WHERE, parses the where clause and
   attaches via set_rust_ast_node_where_clause.
4. Examines the following token:
   - TOKEN_SEMICOLON -> unit struct, advance and return.
   - TOKEN_LPAREN    -> tuple struct: advance, parse_rust_tuple_fields,
     expect TOKEN_RPAREN, expect TOKEN_SEMICOLON, return.
   - TOKEN_LBRACE    -> named struct: advance, parse_rust_struct_fields,
     expect TOKEN_RBRACE, return.
   - otherwise       -> set_rust_parse_error and return 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_struct" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse Rust struct definition

    @Reasoning:
    Parse struct definitions including tuple structs, unit structs, and
    regular structs with named fields. Handle generic parameters, where
    clauses, and derive attributes.
    @End Reasoning

    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_STRUCT from Lexer, "Expected 'struct'"

    Let struct_node be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_STRUCT

    Note: Parse struct name
    Let struct_name be proc peek_rust_token_lexeme from parser
    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer, "Expected struct name"
    proc set_rust_ast_node_name with struct_node, struct_name

    Note: Parse generic parameters
    Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LESS from Lexer:
        Let generics be proc parse_rust_generics from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_generics with struct_node, generics
    End If

    Note: Parse where clause
    Let where_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If where_token is equal to TOKEN_WHERE from Lexer:
        Let where_clause be proc parse_rust_where_clause from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_where_clause with struct_node, where_clause
    End If

    Note: Check struct type
    Let next_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

    If next_token is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
        Note: Unit struct
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
        Return struct_node
    End If

    If next_token is equal to TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer:
        Note: Tuple struct
        proc advance_rust_token from parser  Note: consume '('

        Let fields be proc parse_rust_tuple_fields from parser
        proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with struct_node, fields

        proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')'"
        proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer, "Expected ';'"

        Return struct_node
    End If

    If next_token is equal to TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer:
        Note: Regular struct with named fields
        proc advance_rust_token from parser  Note: consume '{'

        Set fields to proc parse_rust_struct_fields from parser
        proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with struct_node, fields

        proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}'"

        Return struct_node
    End If

    proc set_rust_parse_error with parser, "Expected ';', '(', or '{' after struct name"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Struct field bodies allow each field to carry its own attributes
(`#[serde(default)]` etc.) and visibility modifier. The trailing-
comma allowance is the standard Rust permissiveness so both
`{a: T, b: U}` and `{a: T, b: U,}` are accepted; the loop breaks
when it sees a non-comma after a field, then the caller consumes the
closing brace.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a RUST_PATTERN_STRUCT list node to hold the field nodes. In a
While 1 loop: peeks next token; if TOKEN_RBRACE, breaks. Otherwise
parses attributes via parse_rust_attributes, visibility via
parse_rust_visibility, the field name (TOKEN_IDENTIFIER), and the
required TOKEN_COLON. Calls parse_rust_type for the field type.
Constructs a RUST_PATTERN field_node populated with name, type_info,
attributes, and visibility, and adds it to the fields list. After
each field, if the next token is TOKEN_COMMA advances and continues;
otherwise breaks (the caller handles the closing brace).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_struct_fields" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse named struct fields

    @Reasoning:
    Parse struct fields with visibility, attributes, and types.
    Handle optional trailing commas and field attributes.
    @End Reasoning

    Let fields_list be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_PATTERN_STRUCT

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse field attributes
        Let field_attrs be proc parse_rust_attributes from parser

        Note: Parse field visibility
        Let field_vis be proc parse_rust_visibility from parser

        Note: Parse field name
        Let field_name be proc peek_rust_token_lexeme from parser
        proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer, "Expected field name"

        proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer, "Expected ':'"

        Note: Parse field type
        Let field_type be proc parse_rust_type from parser

        Note: Create field node
        Let field_node be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_PATTERN
        proc set_rust_ast_node_name with field_node, field_name
        proc set_rust_ast_node_type_info with field_node, field_type
        proc set_rust_ast_node_attributes with field_node, field_attrs
        proc set_rust_ast_node_visibility with field_node, field_vis

        proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with fields_list, field_node

        Note: Handle comma separator
        Let comma_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
        If comma_token is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
            proc advance_rust_token from parser
        Otherwise:
            Break  Note: No comma, end of fields
        End If
    End While

    Return fields_list
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Rust functions have several keyword prefixes (`async`, `unsafe`) that
precede the `fn` keyword, followed by name, generics, parameters,
optional return type via `->`, optional where clause, then either a
semicolon (declaration only) or a block body. Recognising the
async/unsafe prefixes before the fn keyword means
parse_rust_function can be called from parse_rust_item without the
caller pre-stripping the modifiers, keeping the item dispatcher
simple.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Checks for and consumes optional TOKEN_ASYNC, setting is_async.
2. Checks for and consumes optional TOKEN_UNSAFE, setting is_unsafe.
3. Consumes the required TOKEN_FN.
4. Creates a RUST_FUNCTION node, calls set_rust_ast_node_async /
   set_rust_ast_node_unsafe with the flags.
5. Reads the function name (TOKEN_IDENTIFIER) and attaches via
   set_rust_ast_node_name.
6. Optionally parses generics if TOKEN_LESS is next; attaches via
   set_rust_ast_node_generics.
7. Consumes TOKEN_LPAREN, parses parameters via
   parse_rust_function_parameters, attaches as child, consumes
   TOKEN_RPAREN.
8. If TOKEN_ARROW is next, advances and parses the return type via
   parse_rust_type, attaching with set_rust_ast_node_type_info.
9. Optionally parses where clause via parse_rust_where_clause.
10. If next token is TOKEN_SEMICOLON, advances (declaration-only
    form). Otherwise parses the body via parse_rust_block_expression
    and attaches as child.
Returns the populated RUST_FUNCTION node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_function" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse Rust function definition

    @Reasoning:
    Parse function definitions including async functions, unsafe functions,
    generic parameters, lifetimes, where clauses, and function bodies.
    Handle const functions and extern functions.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Handle async keyword
    Let is_async be 0
    Let async_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If async_token is equal to TOKEN_ASYNC from Lexer:
        Set is_async to 1
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
    End If

    Note: Handle unsafe keyword
    Let is_unsafe be 0
    Let unsafe_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If unsafe_token is equal to TOKEN_UNSAFE from Lexer:
        Set is_unsafe to 1
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
    End If

    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_FN from Lexer, "Expected 'fn'"

    Let func_node be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_FUNCTION

    Note: Store async/unsafe flags in attributes
    If is_async is equal to 1:
        proc set_rust_ast_node_async with func_node, 1
    End If

    If is_unsafe is equal to 1:
        proc set_rust_ast_node_unsafe with func_node, 1
    End If

    Note: Parse function name
    Let func_name be proc peek_rust_token_lexeme from parser
    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer, "Expected function name"
    proc set_rust_ast_node_name with func_node, func_name

    Note: Parse generic parameters
    Let generics_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If generics_token is equal to TOKEN_LESS from Lexer:
        Let generics be proc parse_rust_generics from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_generics with func_node, generics
    End If

    Note: Parse parameters
    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer, "Expected '('"

    Let params be proc parse_rust_function_parameters from parser
    proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with func_node, params

    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')'"

    Note: Parse return type
    Let arrow_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If arrow_token is equal to TOKEN_ARROW from Lexer:
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
        Let return_type be proc parse_rust_type from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_type_info with func_node, return_type
    End If

    Note: Parse where clause
    Let where_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If where_token is equal to TOKEN_WHERE from Lexer:
        Let where_clause be proc parse_rust_where_clause from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_where_clause with func_node, where_clause
    End If

    Note: Parse function body
    Let body_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

    If body_token is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
        Note: Function declaration only
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
    Otherwise:
        Note: Function definition with body
        Let body be proc parse_rust_block_expression from parser
        proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with func_node, body
    End If

    Return func_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Driver loop over the parameter list. Each entry is built by
parse_rust_function_parameter, which handles all the kinds of
parameters (self, &self, &mut self, pat: type with optional mut).
The comma-separated form with optional trailing comma matches Rust's
allowance for `(a, b,)` syntactic sugar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a RUST_PATTERN params_list node. In a While 1 loop: peeks
next token; if TOKEN_RPAREN, breaks. Otherwise calls
parse_rust_function_parameter; if non-null, adds it as a child of
params_list. If the following token is TOKEN_COMMA, advances and
continues; otherwise breaks. The caller (parse_rust_function) is
responsible for consuming TOKEN_RPAREN after this returns.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_function_parameters" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function parameter list

    @Reasoning:
    Parse function parameters including self parameters, mutable parameters,
    pattern parameters, and type annotations. Handle optional trailing commas.
    @End Reasoning

    Let params_list be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_PATTERN

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse parameter
        Let param be proc parse_rust_function_parameter from parser

        If param is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with params_list, param
        End If

        Note: Handle comma separator
        Let comma_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
        If comma_token is equal to TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer:
            proc advance_rust_token from parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return params_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Rust function parameters come in four shapes that need different
handling: bare `self` (consumed receiver), `&self` / `&mut self`
(borrowed receivers, distinguished by the optional `mut`), and
ordinary `pat: type` parameters with their own optional `mut`
prefix on the pattern side. The self forms are recognised here and
returned as soon as the keyword is consumed because they have no
trailing type annotation - reusing the ordinary `pat: type` path
would emit a spurious "Expected ':'" error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a RUST_PATTERN param_node. Reads the current token:
- TOKEN_SELF: advances, sets name to "self", returns the bare self
  parameter immediately.
- TOKEN_AMP: advances, then checks for an optional TOKEN_MUT and
  sets mutability on the node if present. Then checks for TOKEN_SELF;
  if present, advances and sets name to "&self" before returning.
  (If not self, falls through to the ordinary pattern handling -
  parse_rust_pattern can still consume the &-prefix from there.)
- TOKEN_MUT outside the &-branch: advances and marks the pattern as
  mutable.
After self/mut handling, calls parse_rust_pattern for the pattern,
attaches as child, expects TOKEN_COLON, then parses the type via
parse_rust_type and attaches with set_rust_ast_node_type_info.
Returns the assembled param_node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_function_parameter" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse individual function parameter

    @Reasoning:
    Parse function parameters including self, &self, &mut self, pattern
    parameters with types, and handle mutability modifiers.
    @End Reasoning

    Let param_node be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_PATTERN

    Note: Check for self parameter
    Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SELF from Lexer:
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_name with param_node, "self"
        Return param_node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP from Lexer:
        proc advance_rust_token from parser

        Note: Check for mut after &
        Let mut_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
        If mut_token is equal to TOKEN_MUT from Lexer:
            proc advance_rust_token from parser
            proc set_rust_ast_node_mutability with param_node, 1
        End If

        Let self_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
        If self_token is equal to TOKEN_SELF from Lexer:
            proc advance_rust_token from parser
            proc set_rust_ast_node_name with param_node, "&self"
            Return param_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Handle mut keyword for regular parameters
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MUT from Lexer:
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_mutability with param_node, 1
    End If

    Note: Parse parameter pattern
    Let pattern be proc parse_rust_pattern from parser
    proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with param_node, pattern

    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer, "Expected ':'"

    Note: Parse parameter type
    Let param_type be proc parse_rust_type from parser
    proc set_rust_ast_node_type_info with param_node, param_type

    Return param_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Rust types form a small dispatch tree off the first token: `&` for
references, `*` for raw pointers, `[` for arrays/slices, `(` for
tuples, `fn` for function types, `dyn` for trait objects, and
anything else falls through to a path type (the most common shape -
plain identifiers, qualified paths, generic instantiations). The
dispatch sequence is fixed; each branch hands off to a specialised
parser that consumes its prefix and recursively parses any nested
inner type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads peek_rust_token_type. Dispatches against six punctuation/
keyword tokens in order:
- TOKEN_AMP       -> parse_rust_reference_type
- TOKEN_STAR      -> parse_rust_pointer_type
- TOKEN_LBRACKET  -> parse_rust_array_or_slice_type
- TOKEN_LPAREN    -> parse_rust_tuple_type
- TOKEN_FN        -> parse_rust_function_type
- TOKEN_DYN       -> parse_rust_dyn_type
Falls through to parse_rust_path_type for any other token. The
fallthrough is deliberate so identifier-led types do not require a
new dispatch arm.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse Rust type expression

    @Reasoning:
    Parse all Rust type expressions including references, pointers, slices,
    arrays, tuples, function types, trait objects, and generic types.
    Handle lifetime parameters and mutability.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

    Note: Reference type
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_reference_type from parser
    End If

    Note: Raw pointer type
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STAR from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_pointer_type from parser
    End If

    Note: Array or slice type
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LBRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_array_or_slice_type from parser
    End If

    Note: Tuple type
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_tuple_type from parser
    End If

    Note: Function type
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_function_type from parser
    End If

    Note: Dyn trait object
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DYN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_dyn_type from parser
    End If

    Note: Path type (most common)
    Return proc parse_rust_path_type from parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reference types have four forms (`&T`, `&mut T`, `&'a T`, `&'a mut T`)
that all share the `&` prefix. Parsing each segment separately
(lifetime, then mut, then inner type) lets every combination compose
naturally and stores the lifetime name in the node's `name` slot so
later HIR lowering can recover the lifetime parameter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the leading TOKEN_AMP. Creates a RUST_REFERENCE_TYPE node.
If the next token is TOKEN_LIFETIME, captures its lexeme and stores
via set_rust_ast_node_name, then advances. If the next token is
TOKEN_MUT, advances and calls set_rust_ast_node_mutability with 1.
Recursively parses the referenced type via parse_rust_type and
attaches as child. Returns the assembled ref_node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_reference_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse reference type (&T, &mut T, &'a T, &'a mut T)

    proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_AMP from Lexer, "Expected '&'"

    Let ref_node be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_REFERENCE_TYPE

    Note: Parse optional lifetime
    Let lifetime_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If lifetime_token is equal to TOKEN_LIFETIME from Lexer:
        Let lifetime_name be proc peek_rust_token_lexeme from parser
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_name with ref_node, lifetime_name
    End If

    Note: Parse optional mut keyword
    Let mut_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
    If mut_token is equal to TOKEN_MUT from Lexer:
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
        proc set_rust_ast_node_mutability with ref_node, 1
    End If

    Note: Parse referenced type
    Let inner_type be proc parse_rust_type from parser
    proc add_child_to_rust_ast_node with ref_node, inner_type

    Return ref_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Path types are the workhorse type form - everything from a plain
`bool` to `std::collections::HashMap<K, V>` is a path type. Building
the path as a list of segment names (rather than concatenating
strings with "::") preserves segment boundaries so HIR lowering can
reason about partial paths. Generic argument lists attach to the
preceding segment; their handling continues outside the shown core
loop where they get spliced into the path representation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a RUST_PATH_TYPE node and an empty path_segments List. In a
While 1 loop:
- Reads the current lexeme, expects TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, and pushes the
  lexeme onto path_segments.
- If the next token is TOKEN_LESS, parses generic arguments via
  parse_rust_generic_args.
- If the next token is TOKEN_SCOPE (`::`), advances and continues.
  Otherwise breaks.
After the loop, stores path_segments into the path_node's value slot
via set_rust_ast_node_value. Returns the path_node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_path_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse path type (std::vec::Vec<T>, MyStruct, etc.)

    @Reasoning:
    Parse type paths including module paths, generic arguments, and
    associated types. Handle complex generic syntax with lifetimes.
    @End Reasoning

    Let path_node be proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_PATH_TYPE

    Note: Parse path segments
    Let path_segments be proc create from List

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let segment_name be proc peek_rust_token_lexeme from parser
        proc expect_rust_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer, "Expected identifier"

        proc push from List with path_segments, segment_name

        Note: Check for generic arguments
        Let generic_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
        If generic_token is equal to TOKEN_LESS from Lexer:
            Let generic_args be proc parse_rust_generic_args from parser
            Note: Store generic args with the segment ( for space)
        End If

        Note: Check for path continuation
        Let scope_token be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser
        If scope_token is equal to TOKEN_SCOPE from Lexer:
            proc advance_rust_token from parser  Note: consume '::'
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc set_rust_ast_node_value with path_node, path_segments

    Return path_node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pattern Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Rust patterns dispatch off the first token: `&` for reference
patterns, `mut` for the rare ident-mutability form, `_` for the
wildcard, `(` for tuple patterns, `[` for array/slice patterns,
TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for identifier or qualified-path constructor
patterns, and anything else falls through to a literal pattern.
Returning the wildcard node directly (without delegating to a
specialised parser) is a small optimisation because the wildcard is
the simplest shape - just an empty RUST_PATTERN.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads peek_rust_token_type. Dispatches:
- TOKEN_AMP        -> parse_rust_ref_pattern
- TOKEN_MUT        -> parse_rust_mut_pattern
- TOKEN_UNDERSCORE -> advance and return a fresh RUST_PATTERN node
                       (wildcard).
- TOKEN_LPAREN     -> parse_rust_tuple_pattern
- TOKEN_LBRACKET   -> parse_rust_array_pattern
- TOKEN_IDENTIFIER -> parse_rust_identifier_pattern (which may
                       further refine into struct/tuple/enum
                       patterns based on the trailing tokens).
Falls through to parse_rust_literal_pattern for any other token.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_pattern" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse Rust pattern for destructuring

    @Reasoning:
    Parse all Rust pattern types including identifier patterns, struct patterns,
    tuple patterns, enum patterns, reference patterns, and wildcard patterns.
    Handle nested patterns and pattern guards.
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_rust_token_type from parser

    Note: Reference pattern
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_AMP from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_ref_pattern from parser
    End If

    Note: Mutable pattern
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_MUT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_mut_pattern from parser
    End If

    Note: Wildcard pattern
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_UNDERSCORE from Lexer:
        proc advance_rust_token from parser
        Return proc create_rust_ast_node from RUST_PATTERN
    End If

    Note: Tuple pattern
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_tuple_pattern from parser
    End If

    Note: Array/slice pattern
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LBRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_array_pattern from parser
    End If

    Note: Identifier or path pattern
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_rust_identifier_pattern from parser
    End If

    Note: Literal pattern
    Return proc parse_rust_literal_pattern from parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling and Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Owns the error_message string slot on the parser. Always copies the
caller-supplied message so the lifetime of the stored message is
decoupled from the lifetime of the source string (which may be a
literal in another translation unit). Sets has_error to 1 sticky so
subsequent has_rust_parse_error queries reliably reflect failure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes 1 to offset 24 (has_error flag) of the parser. Calls
StringCore.copy_string to duplicate the message and writes the copy
to offset 16. The previous error_message (if any) is intentionally
not freed here because the convention is one-error-per-parse - the
destructor will reclaim the surviving copy.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_rust_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer:
    Note: Set parser error state with message

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Let error_copy be proc copy_string from StringCore with message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, error_copy
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read accessor for the has_error sticky flag. Consulted by
parse_rust_program after every iteration so the top-level loop can
short-circuit when an item parse fails.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the integer at offset 24 of the parser, which is 0 or 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "has_rust_parse_error" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if parser has encountered an error

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
Setter that takes ownership of a defensive copy of the name string.
Copying decouples the stored name from the lexer's lexeme buffer
(which gets overwritten on the next advance_rust_token), so the AST
node's name remains stable for the lifetime of the tree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns early on null node. Calls StringCore.copy_string to duplicate
the supplied name. Writes the copy to offset 8 of the node. Any
previous name pointer is overwritten without freeing because in
normal use this setter is called exactly once per node, immediately
after create_rust_ast_node.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_rust_ast_node_name" takes node as Integer, name as Integer:
    Note: Set AST node name

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let name_copy be proc copy_string from StringCore with name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name_copy
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stores a parsed attributes list onto the node. Unlike
set_rust_ast_node_name, no copy is made because the attributes list
is already owned by the AST tree (it was constructed during
parse_rust_attributes and only this setter holds a reference to it).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns early on null node. Writes the attributes pointer directly
to offset 40 of the node.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_rust_ast_node_attributes" takes node as Integer, attributes as Integer:
    Note: Set AST node attributes

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, attributes
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stores the visibility level (one of the VIS_* integer constants).
The integer rather than a pointer reflects that visibility is a tag,
not a richer structure - even VIS_PUB_IN, which conceptually carries
a module path, stores its path separately on the parsed visibility
node and only the integer kind lands on the item itself.
@End Reasoning

